Dataset Description: EMDR Therapy for PTSD Study

---

1. Overview

This dataset was generated as part of a quasi-experimental longitudinal study evaluating the effectiveness of Eye Movement Desensitization and Reprocessing (EMDR) therapy on Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder (PTSD) and related mental health outcomes among Intensive Care Unit (ICU) healthcare professionals.

The study was designed to assess both the prevalence of psychological distress and the effectiveness of a structured intervention over time.

---

2. Study Design

- Design Type: Quasi-experimental (pre-test/post-test control group)
- Structure: Longitudinal (repeated measures)
- Time Points:
  - Baseline (pre-intervention)
  - Midline (during/after initial intervention phase)
  - Endline (post-intervention)

- Groups:
  - Treatment group (received EMDR therapy)
  - Control group (no intervention during study period)

---

3. Sample Characteristics

- Total Sample Size: 134 participants
- Population: ICU healthcare professionals
- Roles include:
  - Physicians
  - Nurses

Participants were selected from a clinical healthcare setting and represent a high-risk population for occupational stress and trauma exposure.

---

4. Dataset Structure

- Total Observations: 134
- Total Variables: 60

Note:
The dataset includes both primary (collected) variables and derived variables created during data preparation and analysis. This document focuses on primary and prepared variables relevant to understanding the dataset structure.

---

5. Data Type and Format

- Mixed data types:
  - Continuous variables (e.g., scale scores)
  - Categorical variables (e.g., gender, role)
  - Ordinal/categorized variables (e.g., grouped experience levels)

- Format:
  - Wide format dataset
  - Repeated measures captured as separate variables for each time point

---

6. Variable Categories

6.1 Grouping Variable
- Group: Indicates assignment to Treatment or Control group

---

6.2 Participant Characteristics (Demographics)
- Age: Participant age (years)
- Gender: Participant gender
- MaritalStatus: Marital status category
- Role: Professional role (e.g., Physician, Nurse)
- ICUExperience: Years of experience working in ICU settings
- HoursWeek: Average number of working hours per week

---

6.3 Categorized Demographic Variables

These variables represent grouped versions of continuous measures to support categorical analysis:

- Agegroup: Categorized age bands
- ICUExperienceLength: Grouped ICU experience levels
- WorkingHours: Categorized working hours

---

6.4 Mental Health Outcomes (Continuous Measures)

Mental health outcomes were measured at three time points: baseline, midline, and endline.

PTSD:
- PTSDBaseline
- PTSDMidline
- PTSDEndline

Depression:
- DepressionBaseline
- DepressionMidline
- DepressionEndline

Anxiety:
- AnxietyBaseline
- AnxietyMidline
- AnxietyEndline

---

6.5 Burnout Components

Burnout was assessed using three dimensions:

- Emotional Exhaustion (EE)
- Depersonalization (DP)
- Personal Accomplishment (PA)

Each measured at:
- Baseline
- Midline
- Endline

Examples:
- EEBaseline, EEMidline, EEEndline
- DPBaseline, DPMidline, DPEndline
- PABaseline, PAMidline, PAEndline

---

6.6 Burnout Classification

Categorical burnout status at each time point:

- BurnoutBaseline
- BurnoutMidline
- BurnoutEndline

---

7. Data Preparation Notes

- Data was collected electronically using structured survey tools
- Initial data extraction was performed prior to cleaning and preparation
- Continuous variables were retained for statistical modeling
- Selected variables were categorized to support group comparisons and inferential testing

---

8. Analytical Readiness

The dataset was structured to support:

- Longitudinal analysis (within-subject change over time)
- Between-group comparisons (treatment vs control)
- General Linear Model (GLM)–based methods
- Repeated measures analysis
- Covariate adjustment (e.g., baseline control)

---

9. Derived Variables

Additional variables (e.g., change scores, response indicators, remission indicators) were created during the analysis phase.

These are not detailed in this document and are instead documented within the analysis notes and statistical outputs.

---

10. Data Confidentiality and Ethics

This dataset contains sensitive health-related information and is not publicly shared.

To ensure participant confidentiality:
- No personally identifiable information is included
- Participant codes are anonymized and study-specific
- Data is described at a structural level only

Access to raw data is restricted in accordance with ethical research standards.

---

11. Limitations of the Dataset

- Data is based on self-reported measures
- Context-specific to ICU healthcare professionals in the study setting
- Non-randomized group assignment (quasi-experimental design)

These considerations should be taken into account when interpreting results.

---

12. Usage Notes

This dataset description is provided to support:
- Transparency of the analytical workflow
- Reproducibility of the statistical approach (conceptually)
- Understanding of variable structure and study design

It is not intended for direct data replication due to restricted data access.

